class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> memLeak(int memory1, int memory2) {
        vector<int> res;
        int time = 1;
        while (true) {
            if (memory1 >= time) {
                memory1 -= time;
            } else if (memory2 >= time) {
                memory2 -= time;
            } else {
                res = {time, memory1, memory2};
                break;
            }
            time++;
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(1)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution iterates through the time steps until the program crashes. In each iteration, it checks which memory stick has enough available memory to allocate the current time step. If one stick has enough memory, it allocates the memory and updates the available memory. If neither stick has enough memory, it means the program has crashed, and the solution returns the crash time and available memory for both sticks. The solution has a constant time complexity and space complexity, making it efficient.

